## Responsive Behavior

### Rule FE-011: Mobile-First Implementation

All layout code must be mobile-first: base styles serve the smallest viewport, breakpoint prefixes add complexity for larger screens.

```tsx
// CORRECT: Mobile-first
<div className="flex flex-col gap-4 md:flex-row md:gap-6 lg:gap-8">
  ...
</div>

// INCORRECT: Desktop-first (requires overrides for mobile)
<div className="flex flex-row gap-8 max-md:flex-col max-md:gap-4">
  ...
</div>
```

### Rule FE-012: Breakpoints from Design System Only

Use only the breakpoints defined in `docs/design-system/RESPONSIVE-SYSTEM.md`. Do not introduce custom breakpoints.

Breakpoint names in code must match the design system names exactly (e.g., if the design system defines `md` as 768px, the code uses `md:` — never `min-[768px]:`).

### Rule FE-013: Touch Targets on Mobile

Interactive elements must have a minimum touch target of 44×44px on mobile viewports (DS-020). If the visual size of an element is smaller, use padding or a pseudo-element to extend the touch area.

```tsx
// CORRECT: Small icon button with adequate touch target
<button
  className="p-2 md:p-1.5" // 40px → 36px on desktop (where mouse is used)
  aria-label="Close"
>
  <CloseIcon className="w-5 h-5" />
</button>

// INCORRECT: Icon button with inadequate touch target on mobile
<button className="p-1" aria-label="Close">
  <CloseIcon className="w-4 h-4" /> // Only 24px touch target
</button>
```

