## Accessibility in Code

### Rule FE-016: Accessible Names for Interactive Elements

Every interactive element must have an accessible name. Buttons and links must have descriptive text, or an `aria-label` if icon-only.

```tsx
// CORRECT: Icon button with aria-label
<button aria-label="Delete pipeline">
  <TrashIcon aria-hidden="true" />
</button>

// CORRECT: Button with visible text
<button>Delete pipeline</button>

// INCORRECT: Icon button without accessible name
<button>
  <TrashIcon />
</button>
```

### Rule FE-017: Focus Management in Dynamic Content

When content changes dynamically (modals open, drawers slide, route changes), focus must be managed explicitly.

```tsx
// Modal: focus moves to first focusable element on open
// Drawer: focus moves to drawer container or first interactive element
// Route change: focus moves to page heading or skip link
// Toast: focus is NOT moved (toast is non-blocking)
// Inline error: focus stays where it is; error is announced via aria-live
```

### Rule FE-018: Semantic HTML First

Use semantic HTML elements before ARIA. ARIA supplements semantics — it does not replace them.

```tsx
// CORRECT: Semantic HTML
<nav aria-label="Main navigation">
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/learn">Learn</a></li>
  </ul>
</nav>

// INCORRECT: Div soup with ARIA
<div role="navigation" aria-label="Main navigation">
  <div role="list">
    <div role="listitem"><span role="link" tabIndex={0}>Learn</span></div>
  </div>
</div>
```

