## Pillar Token Overrides

### Rule FE-019: Pillar Tokens Applied via CSS Scope

Pillar-specific token overrides are applied by wrapping the pillar's root layout element with a CSS class or data attribute that defines the pillar tokens. Components inside do not check which pillar they render in — they always use pillar tokens.

```tsx
// CORRECT: Pillar root applies overrides; components inside are pillar-agnostic
<div data-pillar="learn" className="pillar-learn">
  <Card /> // uses --pillar-accent, --pillar-body-size, etc. without knowing "learn"
</div>

// INCORRECT: Component checks which pillar it is in
function Card({ pillar }: { pillar: 'learn' | 'hub' | 'labs' }) {
  const accentColor = pillar === 'learn' ? '#0FA87F' : '#8B5CF6'; // hardcoded per pillar
  return <div style={{ borderColor: accentColor }} />;
}
```

### Rule FE-020: Primary Action Color Is Never Overridden per Pillar

The primary action color (`--action-primary`, used for buttons, links, focus rings) must be identical across all pillars. It must not be assigned the pillar accent color. This is an absolute constraint from DS-018.

```tsx
// CORRECT: Primary button uses action-primary everywhere
<Button variant="primary" className="bg-action-primary hover:bg-action-primary-hover">
  Start learning
</Button>

// INCORRECT: Overriding action color with pillar accent
<Button className="bg-pillar-accent hover:bg-pillar-accent-hover">
  Start learning
</Button>
```

